hoon Nangka|Nangka]]||[[Typhoon Soudelor (disambiguation)|Saudel]]||[[Typhoon Molave|Molave]]||[[Typhoon Goni|Goni]]||[[Typhoon Morakot (disambiguation)|Atsani]]||[[Typhoon Etau|Etau]]||[[Typhoon Vamco|Vamco]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" rowspan=2| 4\n|[[Typhoon Krovanh|Krovanh]]||[[Typhoon Dujuan|Dujuan]]||[[Typhoon Mujigae (disambiguation)|Surigae]]||[[Typhoon Choi-wan|Choi-wan]]||[[List of tropical storms named Koppu|Koguma]]||[[Typhoon Ketsana (disambiguation)|Champi]]||[[Typhoon Parma (disambiguation)|In-fa]]||[[Typhoon Melor (disambiguation)|Cempaka]]||[[Typhoon Nepartak|Nepartak]]||[[Typhoon Lupit|Lupit]]||[[Typhoon Mirinae|Mirinae]]||[[Typhoon Nida|Nida]]||[[Tropical Storm Omais|Omais]]||[[Typhoon Conson|Conson]]\n|-\n|[[Typhoon Chanthu|Chanthu]]||[[Typhoon Dianmu|Dianmu]]||[[Typhoon Mindulle|Mindulle]]||[[Typhoon Lionrock|Lionrock]]||[[Typhoon Kompasu|Kompasu]]||[[Typhoon Namtheun|Namtheun]]||[[Tropical Storm Malou|Malou]]||[[List of tropical storms named Meranti|Nyatoh]]||[[Typhoon Rananim (disambiguation)|Rai]]||[[Typhoon Malakas|Malakas]]||[[Typhoon Megi|Megi]]||[[Typhoon Chaba|Chaba]]||[[Typhoon Aere|Aere]]||[[Typhoon Songda|Songda]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" rowspan=2| 5\n|[[Typhoon Sarika (disambiguation)|Trases]]||[[Tropical Storm Haima|Mulan]]||[[Typhoon Meari|Meari]]||[[Typhoon Ma-on|Ma-on]]||[[Typhoon Tokage|Tokage]]||[[Typhoon Nock-ten (disambiguation)|Hinnamnor]]||[[Typhoon Muifa|Muifa]]||[[Typhoon Merbok|Merbok]]||[[Typhoon Nanmadol|Nanmadol]]||[[Typhoon Talas|Talas]]||[[Typhoon Noru|Noru]]||[[Tropical Storm Kulap|Kulap]]||[[Typhoon Roke|Roke]]||[[Typhoon Sonca|Sonca]]\n|-\n|[[Typhoon Nesat|Nesat]]||[[Typhoon Haitang|Haitang]]||[[Typhoon Nalgae|Nalgae]]||[[Typhoon Banyan|Banyan]]||[[Tropical Storm Hato|Yamaneko]]||[[Tropical Storm Pakhar|Pakhar]]||[[Tropical Storm Sanvu|Sanvu]]||[[Typhoon Mawar|Mawar]]||[[Typhoon Guchol|Guchol]]||[[Typhoon Talim|Talim]]||[[Tropical Storm Doksuri|Doksuri]]||[[Typhoon Khanun|Khanun]]||[[Tropical Storm Vicente|Lan]]||[[Typhoon Saola|Saola]]\n|-\n!colspan=20|References:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jma.go.jp/jma/jma-eng/jma-center/rsmc-hp-pub-eg/tyname.html|title=List of names for tropical cyclones adopted by the ESCAP/WMO Typhoon Committee for the western North Pacific and the South China Sea (valid as of 2019)|date=|website=[[Japan Meteorological Agency]]: [[Regional Specialized Meteorological Center|RSMC Tokyo - Typhoon Center]]|publisher=Japan Meteorological Agency|author=RSMC Tokyo-Typhoon Center|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 25, 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== Records ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:300px; text-align:center; margin:0 1em; float:right;clear:right;\" HL +\n|-\n! Total<br />storms\n! Year\n! Tropical<br />storms\n! Typhoons\n! Super<br />typhoons\n|-\n| 39 || [[1964 Pacific typhoon season|1964]] || 13 || 19 || 7\n|-\n| 35 || [[1965 Pacific typhoon season|1965]]<br />[[1967 Pacific typhoon season|1967]]<br />[[1971 Pacific typhoon season|1971]] || 14<br />15<br />11 || 10<br />16<br />16 || 11<br />4<br />4\n|-\n| 34 || [[1994 Pacific typhoon season|1994]] || 14 || 14 || 6\n|-\n| 33 || [[1996 Pacific typhoon season|1996]] || 12 || 15 || 6\n|-\n| 32 || [[1974 Pacific typhoon season|1974]] || 16 || 16 || 0\n|-\n| 31 || [[1989 Pacific typhoon season|1989]]<br />[[1992 Pacific typhoon season|1992]]<br />[[2013 Pacific typhoon season|2013]] || 10<br />13<br />18 || 15<br />17<br />8 || 6<br />5<br />5\n|-\n| 30 || [[1962 Pacific typhoon season|1962]]<br />[[1966 Pacific typhoon season|1966]]<br />[[1972 Pacific typhoon season|1972]]<br />[[1990 Pacific typhoon season|1990]]<br />[[2004 Pacific typhoon season|2004]] || 7<br />10<br />8<br />9<br />10<br /> || 17<br />17<br />20<br />17<br />13 || 6<br />3<br />2<br />4<br />7\n|}\nThe most active Western Pacific typhoon season was in 1964,{{citation needed|date=September 2012}} when 39&nbsp;storms of tropical storm strength formed. Only 15 seasons had 30 or more storms developing since reliable records began. The least activity seen in the northwest Pacific Ocean was during the [[2010 Pacific typhoon season]], when only 14&nbsp;tropical storms and seven typhoons formed. In the Philippines, the most active season, since 1945, for tropical cyclone strikes was [[1993 Pacific typhoon season|1993]] when nineteen tropical cyclones moved through the country.<ref>{{cite web|author=Joint Typhoon Warning Center|year=2009|url=http://www.typhooncommittee.org/41st/docs/TC2_MemberReport2008_PHILIPPINES1.pdf|title=Member Report Republic of the Philippines|work=[[Philippine Atmospheric, Geophysical and Astronomical Services Administration]]|publisher=[[World Meteorological Organization]]|accessdate=2010-04-14|author-link=Joint Typhoon Warning Center}}</ref> There was only one tropical cyclone that moved through the Philippines in [[1958 Pacific typhoon season|1958]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Joint Typhoon Warning Center|year=1959|title=1958|publisher=[[United States Navy]]|author-link=Joint Typhoon Warning Center}}</ref> The [[2004 Pacific typhoon season]] was the busiest for Okinawa since 1957.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.stripes.com/news/preparation-critical-for-japan-s-coming-typhoon-season-1.33979|publisher=Stars and Stripes|title=Preparation critical for Japan's coming typhoon season|author=Erik Slavin|date=2005-05-30|accessdate=2011-03-06}}</ref> Within [[Guangdong]] in southern China, during the past thousand years, the most active decades for typhoon strikes were the 1660s and 1670s.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Annals of the Association of American Geographers|year=2001|author1=Kam-Biu Liu |author2=Caiming Shen |author3=Kin-Sheun Louie  |last-author-amp=yes |title=A 1,000-Year History of Typhoon Landfalls in Guangdong, Southern China, Reconstructed from Chinese Historical Documentary Records|volume=91|issue=3|pages=453\u2013464|issn=0004-5608|doi=10.1111/0004-5608.00253}}</ref>\n\nThe highest reliably-estimated [[maximum sustained winds]] on record for a typhoon were those of [[Typhoon Haiyan]] at {{convert|195|mph|km/h|order=flip|abbr=on}} shortly before its landfall in the central [[Philippines]] on November 8, 2013.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/capital-weather-gang/wp/2013/11/07/super-typhoon-haiyan-closes-in-on-philippines-among-strongest-storms-ever/|title=Among Strongest Storms Ever |last=Samenow |first=Jason |author2=McNoldy Brian |work=The Washington Post |date=2013-11-08 |accessdate=2013-11-08}}</ref> The most intense storm based on minimum pressure was [[Typhoon Tip]] in the northwestern Pacific Ocean in 1979, which reached a minimum pressure of {{Convert|870|hPa|inHg}} and maximum sustained wind speeds of 165&nbsp;knots (85&nbsp;m/s, 190&nbsp;mph, 310&nbsp;km/h).<ref name=\"JTWC\">{{cite journal|author1=George M. Dunnavan |author2=John W. Diercks |year=1980|issue=11|pages=1915\u20131923|title=An Analysis of Super Typhoon Tip (October 1979)|journal=Monthly Weather Review|volume=108|doi=10.1175/1520-0493(1980)108<1915:AAOSTT>2.0.CO;2|bibcode = 1980MWRv..108.1915D|issn=1520-0493 }}</ref> The deadliest typhoon of the 20th century was [[Typhoon Nina (1975)|Typhoon Nina]], which killed nearly 100,000 in China in 1975 due to a flood that caused 12 reservoirs to fail.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/iwtc/AndersonBerry5-1.html|title=Fifth International Workshop on Tropycal Cyclones: Topic 5.1: Societal Impacts of Tropical Cyclones.|last=Anderson-Berry|first=Linda J.|author2=Weyman James C. |date=2008-02-26|work=World Meteorological Organization|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|accessdate=2011-03-31}}</ref> After [[Typhoon Morakot]] landed in Taiwan at midnight on August 8, 2009, almost the entire southern region of Taiwan ([[Chiayi County]]/[[Chiayi City]], [[Tainan County]]/[[Tainan City]] (now merged as Tainan), [[Kaohsiung County]]/[[Kaohsiung City]] (now merged as Kaohsiung), and [[Pingtung County]]) and parts of [[Taitung County]] and [[Nantou County]] were flooded by record-breaking heavy rain. The rainfall in [[Pingtung County]] reached 2,327 millimeters (91.6&nbsp;in),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wmo.asu.edu/Taiwan-rainfall-record-investigation|author=Arizona State University|title=Taiwan Rainfall Record Investigation|date=2009-08-12|accessdate=2011-03-06|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110102193453/http://wmo.asu.edu/Taiwan-rainfall-record-investigation|archivedate=2011-01-02|df=}}</ref> breaking all rainfall records of any single place in Taiwan induced by a single typhoon,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chinapost.com.tw/taiwan/national/national-news/2009/08/09/219677/RECORD-RAINS.htm|title=Record rains in south|publisher=The China Post|accessdate=2009-08-09|date=2009-08-09|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5ixk4jA1t?url=http://www.chinapost.com.tw/taiwan/national/national-news/2009/08/09/219677/RECORD-RAINS.htm|archivedate=2009-08-12|df=}}</ref> and making the cyclone the wettest known typhoon.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Tropical cyclones}}\n* [[China tropical cyclone rainfall climatology]]\n* [[Effects of tropical cyclones]]\n* [[Tropical cyclone]]\n* [[Typhoons in the Philippines]]\n* [[List of Pacific typhoon seasons]]\n* [[{{CURRENTYEAR}} Pacific typhoon season]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=nb}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{WPAC EL's}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n{{Cyclones}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pacific Typhoon}}\n[[Category:Tropical cyclone meteorology]]\n[[Category:Typhoons| ]]\n", "name_user": "G980849491", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(For homework)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Typhoon"}
{"title_page": "James Dubik", "text_new": "{{short description|American Lieutenant General}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name          = James Dubik\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image_upright = https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/f3/James_M._Dubik.jpg\n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| native_name   = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name    = \n| other_name    = \n| nickname      = Jim Dubik\n| birth_date    = <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = <!--{{death date and age|dYYYY|dMM|dDD|YYYY|MM|DD}}-->\n| death_place   = \n| placeofburial = \n| placeofburial_label = \n| placeofburial_coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}}-->\n| allegiance    = [[United States]]\n| branch        = [[United States Army]]\n| branch_label  = Service\n| serviceyears  = \n| serviceyears_label = \n| rank          = Lieutenant General\n| rank_label    = Rank\n| servicenumber = \n| unit          = \n| commands      = \n| battles       = \n| battles_label = \n| awards        = \n| memorials     = \n| spouse        = <!--Add spouse if reliably sourced-->\n| children      = \n| relations     = \n| laterwork     = Writer, <br /> [[Philosophy]] professor\n| signature     = \n| signature_size = \n| signature_alt = \n| website       = {{URL|https://twitter.com/ltgrdubik}}\n| module        = \n}}\nLieutenant General James M. Dubik (U.S. Army, Ret.) is a Senior Fellow at the Institute for the Study of War and a Professor at Georgetown University's Security Studies Program. General Dubik has extensive operational experience in Iraq, Afghanistan, Japan, Korea, Thailand, Bosnia, Haiti, Panama, Honduras, and in many NATO countries.\n\nHis last job on active duty was as Commanding General of the Multinational Security Transition Command-Iraq (MNSTC-I) and the NATO Training Mission-Iraq during the Surge of 2007\u20132008. He is a member of the U.S. Army Ranger Hall of Fame and a distinguished member of the U.S. Army 75th Ranger Regiment.\n\nGeneral Dubik taught Philosophy at West Point and Campaign Theory and Practice at the U.S. Army School of Advanced Military Studies, Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.\u00a0 He has completed an MIT fellowship program for national security studies as well as executive programs in national security at Harvard's JFK School of Government and Syracuse University's Maxwell School of Citizenship and Public Affairs. He is the author, most recently, of ''Just War Reconsidered: Strategy, Ethics, and Theory.''\n\n==Education ==\nDubik received a bachelor's degree in Philosophy from [[Gannon University]] in Erie, Pennsylvania.   He received  a master's degree in Military Arts and Sciences from the Army Command and General Staff College at Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://hertogfoundation.org/staff/james-m-dubik|title=James M. Dubik|website=Hertog Foundation}}</ref> Dubik earned a PhD in philosophy from [[Johns Hopkins University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.americamagazine.org/voices/james-m-dubik|title=James M. Dubik|website=America Magazine}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\n==Military career ==\nDubik served as Commanding General for the Multi National Security Transition Command-Iraq.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.c-span.org/person/?jamesdubik|title=James M. Dubik &#124; C-SPAN.org|website=www.c-span.org}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtoninstitute.org/experts/view/james-dubik|title=James Dubik - The Washington Institute for Near East Policy|website=www.washingtoninstitute.org}}</ref>\n\nHe taught philosophy at the [[United States Military Academy]].<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nDubik retired from the Army in 2008.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n==Civilian career==\nDubik currently serves as the Senior Fellow at the [[Institute for the Study of War]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.understandingwar.org/press-media/staff-bios/lt-gen-ret-james-dubik|title=LTG. (R) James M. Dubik|website=Institute for the Study of War}}</ref>  He has written for various journals, including Foreign Policy magazine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/author/lt-gen-james-m-dubik/|title=Lt. Gen. James M. Dubik \u2013 Foreign Policy}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works ==\n* ''Waging War and Using Force''. Naval Institute Press, forthcoming.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n* ''Just War Reconsidered: Strategy, Ethics, and Theory''. Lexington, Kentucky : University Press of Kentucky, 2018. {{ISBN|0813175011}} {{OCLC|1001533501}}\n* ''Accelerating Combat Power in Afghanistan''. 2009. {{OCLC|822967215}}\n* ''Has Warfare Changed?: Sorting Apples from Oranges''. Arlington, Va: Institute of Land Warfare, Association of the United States Army, 2002. {{OCLC|\t50556506}}\n* ''The Army's \"Twofer\": The Dual Role of the Interim Force''. Arlington, Va: Institute of Land Warfare, Association of the United States Army, 2001. {{OCLC|48215274}}\n* With Gordon R. Sullivan. ''Envisioning Future Warfare'' 1995. Reissued in 2003. {{OCLC|53114595}}\n\n==Personal life ==\nDubik lives in Arlington, Virginia.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dubik, James}}\n[[Category:American military officers]]\n[[Category:American writers]]\n[[Category:Gannon University alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Military Academy faculty]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American Lieutenant General}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name          = James Dubik\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image_upright = https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/f3/James_M._Dubik.jpg\n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| native_name   = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name    = \n| other_name    = \n| nickname      = Jim Dubik\n| birth_date    = <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = <!--{{death date and age|dYYYY|dMM|dDD|YYYY|MM|DD}}-->\n| death_place   = \n| placeofburial = \n| placeofburial_label = \n| placeofburial_coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}}-->\n| allegiance    = [[United States]]\n| branch        = [[United States Army]]\n| branch_label  = Service\n| serviceyears  = \n| serviceyears_label = \n| rank          = Lieutenant General\n| rank_label    = Rank\n| servicenumber = \n| unit          = \n| commands      = \n| battles       = \n| battles_label = \n| awards        = \n| memorials     = \n| spouse        = <!--Add spouse if reliably sourced-->\n| children      = \n| relations     = \n| laterwork     = Writer, <br /> [[Philosophy]] professor\n| signature     = \n| signature_size = \n| signature_alt = \n| website       = {{URL|https://twitter.com/ltgrdubik}}\n| module        = \n}}\nLieutenant General James M. Dubik (U.S. Army, Ret.) is a Senior Fellow at the Institute for the Study of War and a Professor at Georgetown University\u2019s Security Studies Program. General Dubik has extensive operational experience in Iraq, Afghanistan, Japan, Korea, Thailand, Bosnia, Haiti, Panama, Honduras, and in many NATO countries.\n\nHis last job on active duty was as Commanding General of the Multinational Security Transition Command-Iraq (MNSTC-I) and the NATO Training Mission-Iraq during the Surge of 2007\u20132008. He is a member of the U.S. Army Ranger Hall of Fame and a distinguished member of the U.S. Army 75th Ranger Regiment.\n\nGeneral Dubik taught Philosophy at West Point and Campaign Theory and Practice at the U.S. Army School of Advanced Military Studies, Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.\u00a0 He has completed an MIT fellowship program for national security studies as well as executive programs in national security at Harvard\u2019s JFK School of Government and Syracuse University\u2019s Maxwell School of Citizenship and Public Affairs. He is the author, most recently, of ''Just War Reconsidered: Strategy, Ethics, and Theory.''\n\n==Education ==\nDubik received a bachelor's degree in Philosophy from [[Gannon University]] in Erie, Pennsylvania.   He received  a master's degree in Military Arts and Sciences from the Army Command and General Staff College at Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://hertogfoundation.org/staff/james-m-dubik|title=James M. Dubik|website=Hertog Foundation}}</ref> Dubik earned a PhD in philosophy from [[Johns Hopkins University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.americamagazine.org/voices/james-m-dubik|title=James M. Dubik|website=America Magazine}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\n==Military career ==\nDubik served as Commanding General for the Multi National Security Transition Command-Iraq.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.c-span.org/person/?jamesdubik|title=James M. Dubik &#124; C-SPAN.org|website=www.c-span.org}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtoninstitute.org/experts/view/james-dubik|title=James Dubik - The Washington Institute for Near East Policy|website=www.washingtoninstitute.org}}</ref>\n\nHe taught philosophy at the [[United States Military Academy]].<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nDubik retired from the Army in 2008.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n==Civilian career==\nDubik currently serves as the Senior Fellow at the [[Institute for the Study of War]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.understandingwar.org/press-media/staff-bios/lt-gen-ret-james-dubik|title=LTG. (R) James M. Dubik|website=Institute for the Study of War}}</ref>  He has written for various journals, including Foreign Policy magazine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/author/lt-gen-james-m-dubik/|title=Lt. Gen. James M. Dubik \u2013 Foreign Policy}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works ==\n* ''Waging War and Using Force''. Naval Institute Press, forthcoming.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n* ''Just War Reconsidered: Strategy, Ethics, and Theory''. Lexington, Kentucky : University Press of Kentucky, 2018. {{ISBN|0813175011}} {{OCLC|1001533501}}\n* ''Accelerating Combat Power in Afghanistan''. 2009. {{OCLC|822967215}}\n* ''Has Warfare Changed?: Sorting Apples from Oranges''. Arlington, Va: Institute of Land Warfare, Association of the United States Army, 2002. {{OCLC|\t50556506}}\n* ''The Army's \"Twofer\": The Dual Role of the Interim Force''. Arlington, Va: Institute of Land Warfare, Association of the United States Army, 2001. {{OCLC|48215274}}\n* With Gordon R. Sullivan. ''Envisioning Future Warfare'' 1995. Reissued in 2003. {{OCLC|53114595}}\n\n==Personal life ==\nDubik lives in Arlington, Virginia.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dubik, James}}\n[[Category:American military officers]]\n[[Category:American writers]]\n[[Category:Gannon University alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Military Academy faculty]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (3)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Dubik"}
{"title_page": "Gregory H. Williams", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix   = \n|name               = Gregory Howard Williams\n|honorific-suffix   =\n|image              =\n|imagesize          =\n|smallimage         = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n|alt                =\n|caption            =\n|office             = 28th [[University of Cincinnati|President of University of Cincinnati]]\n|term_start         = 2009\n|term_end           = 2012\n|predecessor        = [[Nancy L. Zimpher]]\n|successor          = [[Santa J. Ono]]\n|order2             =\n|office2            = 11th President of [[the City College of New York]]\n|term_start2        = 2001\n|term_end2          = 2009\n|predecessor2       = Stanford A. Roman Jr., interim; [[Yolanda T. Moses]], President\n|successor2         = Robert \"Buzz\" Paaswell, interim; [[Lisa Staiano-Coico]], President\n| office3           = 17th Dean of [[Moritz College of Law]]\n| term_start3       = 1993\n| term_end3         = 2001\n| predecessor3      = [[Francis X. Beytagh]]\n| successor3        = [[Nancy H. Rogers]]\n| alma_mater        = [[George Washington University]]\n}}\n\n'''Gregory Howard Williams''' is a scholar, attorney, law school professor, author, and formerly the 27th President of the [[University of Cincinnati]] (2009 to 2012)<ref>{{cite web|title=Dr. Gregory H. Williams|url=https://cityclub.org|website=The City Club of Clevland|accessdate=11 June 2016}}</ref> and the 11th President of [[the City College of New York]] (2001 - 2009).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Simon|first1=Ellis|title=CCNY President DR. Gregory H. Williams Resigns To Become President Of University Of Cincinnati|url=https://www.ccny.cuny.edu/news/CCNY-PRESIDENT-GREGORY-WILLIAMS-RESIGNS-TO-BECOME-PRESIDENT-OF-UNIVERSITY-OF-CINCINNATI|website=The City College of New York|publisher=City University of New York|date=September 9, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Holmes|first1=Marie|title=College President Series: Gregory H. Williams: President, City College|url=http://www.educationupdate.com/archives/2002/oct02/issue/col-collegepres.htm|publisher=Education Update, Inc.|date=October 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Mabunda|first1=L Mpho|last2=Phelps|first2=Shirelle|title=Contemporary Black biography. Volume 11 : profiles from the international Black community|date=1996|publisher=Gale Research Inc.|location=Detroit, Mich|isbn=9781414435398|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education ==\nGregory Howard Williams was born on November 12, 1943, in [[Muncie, Indiana]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thehistorymakers.org/biography/gregory-h-williams-41|title=Gregory H. Williams {{!}} The HistoryMakers|website=www.thehistorymakers.org|language=en|access-date=2018-02-11}}</ref> He was the son of James Anthony, a businessman, and Mary, a homemaker. He grew up in [[Gum Spring, Virginia]], until his parents separated, and his father lost his business. At the age of ten years old, Williams and his brother moved to [[Muncie, Indiana]]<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Moten-Foster |display-authors=etal |first1=Bea|authorlink=Bea Moten-Foster|title=Gregory Howard Williams|journal=Muncie Times|date=May 5, 2002|volume=11|issue=9|url=https://www.worldcat.org|publisher=The Muncie Times|location=Muncie, Indiana}}</ref> where his father had family, and he first became aware of his father's [[African American]] heritage.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Perry|first1=Michael|title=UC's new president has a powerful story to tell|url=http://www.gobearcats.com/sports/ucats/spec-rel/120809aag.html|website=gobearcats.com|publisher=CBS Interactive|date=December 8, 2009}}</ref> Despite a period of confusion about his own identity, Williams embraced his father's passion for education.<ref>{{cite web|title=The History Makers: The Nation's Largest African American Oral History Collection|url=http://www.thehistorymakers.com|accessdate=May 16, 2007}}</ref>\n\nWilliams earned a bachelor of arts degree from [[Ball State University]] in 1966, where he paid tuition by earning money as a [[deputy sheriff]] in the Delaware County Sheriff's Department in [[Muncie, Indiana]], from 1963 to 1966. Between 1966 and 1970, Williams taught classes in Virginia state government and history George Mason Junior \u2013 Senior High School in [[Falls Church, Virginia]]. In 1969, he earned a master's degree in government and politics from [[University of Maryland]]. Williams earned a J.D. from [[George Washington University]] in 1971. From 1971 to 1973, Williams was a legislative assistant to Senator [[Vance Hartke]] (D-Indiana) of the [[United States Senate]], [[Washington, D.C.]]. In 1977, Williams earned a master's degree in political science, and in 1982, a doctorate in political science, both from [[George Washington University]] with a thesis \"Legal and political problems of police discretion\".<ref>{{cite thesis|last1=Williams|first1=Gregory Howard|title=Legal and political problems of police discretion|date=1982|degree=Ph.D.|publisher=George Washington University|oclc=10315748}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Rieselman|first1=Deborah|title=New UC president Gregory Williams embraces diversity|url=http://magazine.uc.edu/issues/1009/president.html|website=UC Magazine|publisher=University of Cincinnati}}</ref> He also earned an MBA from [[Mercy College (New York)]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://educationupdate.com/homeroom/2017/03/mercy-college.html#.WQt1fegrKUk|title=Mercy College Hosts 36th Annual Mercy College Trustees' Scholarship Dinner - Homeroom|website=educationupdate.com|access-date=2019-10-30}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nWilliams joined the [[University of Iowa]] Law faculty in 1977, where he taught [[criminal law]], [[criminal procedure]], and [[legislation]]. Williams was faculty scholar from 1990 to 1993. At Iowa, Williams served as [[Associate Dean]] of the Law School, from 1977 to 1993, where he oversaw admissions, financial aid, student and faculty recruitment, and student support, and he served as Associate Vice President of Academic Affairs from 1991\u201393.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gregory H.Williams|url=http://library.law.uiowa.edu|website=University of Iowa Law Library|publisher=The University of Iowa|accessdate=11 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1975 to 1977, he consulted to the Foreign Lawyer Training Program in [[Washington, DC]]. He was a member of the Iowa State Advisory Commission to the [[United States Civil Rights Commission]] from 1978 to 1988, and a member of the Iowa Law Enforcement Academy Council from 1979 to 1985.<ref>{{cite web|title=Williams, Gregory 1943|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com|website=Encyclopedia.com|accessdate=11 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nWilliams was appointed visiting professor on faculty of law at [[Durham University]], [[Durham, England]], from 1984 to 1986, and visiting scholar at [[Selwyn College, Cambridge|Selwyn College]] at [[Cambridge University]], [[Cambridge, England]], from 1986 to 1987.\n\nFrom 1991 to 1993, he held the position of Associate Vice-President for Academic Affairs at the [[University of Iowa]] in [[Iowa City, Iowa]]. From 1993 to 2001, Williams held the positions of Carter Kissell Professor of Law and Dean of the Michael E. [[Moritz College of Law]] at [[Ohio State University]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Arenson|first1=Karen W.|title=Ohio Law School Dean Is Named As New President of City College|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/03/27/nyregion/ohio-law-school-dean-is-named-as-new-president-of-city-college.html|newspaper=NY Times|date=March 27, 2001}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Lassiter|first1=Luke E|title=The other side of Middletown : exploring Muncie's African American community|date=2004|publisher=AltaMira Press|location=Walnut Creek, CA|isbn=0759104832|page=41|url=http://www.worldcat.org}}</ref> While Dean, the size of the faculty increased by 40 percent, the number of named chairs and professorships doubled, and $25 million was raised from alumni of approximately 7,000 graduates.<ref>{{cite web|title=Prominent Law School Dean Gregory H. Williams Named City College President|url=http://www1.cuny.edu/mu/forum/2001/03/26/prominent-law-school-dean-gregory-h-williams-named-city-college-president/|website=CUNY|publisher=The City University of New York|date=March 26, 2001}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Rose|first1=Derek|last2=Hutchinson|first2=Bill|title=11th CCNY Prez Named \u2014 Ohio law school dean, author to head school|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/11th-ccny-prez-named-ohio-law-school-dean-author-head-school-article-1.914545|work=Daily News|date=March 27, 2001}}</ref>\n\n===College presidencies===\nIn 2001, Williams was appointed the 11th President of [[the City College of New York]] - the flagship campus of the [[City University of New York]] system. His appointment followed his tenure as a law school dean at [[Ohio State]] since 1993, where Williams taught courses in criminal law, he raised $25 million and oversaw the increase of the school's endowment by about 50 percent.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Arenson|first1=Karen W.|title=2 Law School Deans Are Finalists for City College Presidency|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/03/18/nyregion/2-law-school-deans-are-finalists-for-city-college-presidency.html|work=The New York Times|date=March 18, 2001}}</ref> During his tenure at Ohio State, Williams also served as the president of the Association of American Law Schools and his autobiographical book, ''Life on the Color Line: The True Story of a White Boy Who Discovered He Was Black'', (Dutton, 1995) won the 1995 Los Angeles Times Book Award.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Arenson|first1=Karen W.|title=The President Of City College May Leave Post|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/12/12/nyregion/the-president-of-city-college-may-leave-post.html|work=The New York Times|date=December 12, 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Graff|first1=E.|title=Being Black and White|url=http://prospect.org/article/being-black-and-white|website=The American Prospect|date=December 10, 2001}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.cuny.edu/events/cunymatters/2001_summer/collegepresidency.html|title=Midwestern Law School Dean Assumes City College Presidency|last=|first=|date=|website=CUNY Matters|publisher=City University of New Yorkj|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nUnder Williams' presidency of [[the City College of New York]], enrollment increased by 60&nbsp;percent and academic standards improved significantly; nearly 90&nbsp;percent of the student body continue to represent racial minority groups.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|last1=Foderaro|first1=Lisa W.|title=President of City College Is Taking Helm at Cincinnati|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/10/nyregion/10ccny.html|newspaper=NY Times|date=September 9, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Rivers|first1=Voza|last2=Williams|first2=Lloyd A|title=Forever Harlem: Celebrating America's Most Diverse Community|date=2006|publisher=Sports Pub.|location=Champaign, Ill.|isbn=9781596702066|page=256|url=http://www.worldcat.org}}</ref> Williams successfully oversaw the first [[capital campaign]] at City College,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mwamba|first1=Jay|title=CCNY'S 160th Commencement Set For June 1; President Gregory Williams To Address Graduates|url=http://www1.cuny.edu/mu/forum/2006/05/25/ccnys-160th-commencement-set-for-june-1-president-gregory-williams-to-address-graduates/|website=City College of New York|publisher=City University of New York|date=May 25, 2006}}</ref> raising more than $230 million and effectively establishing a culture of philanthropy, and more than doubled City College's research funding.\n\nDuring his tenure as president of [[the City College of New York]], Williams served as Chair of the Commission on Access, Diversity, and Excellence (CADE) of the [[Association of Public and Land-grant Universities]]. Williams moderated and presented at the 2001 Association of American Law Schools annual meeting.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Chander|first1=Anupam|last2=Coates|first2=John C|last3=Association of American Law Schools|title=AALS scholarly paper presentation|date=2001|url=https://www.worldcat.org|publisher=Recorded Resources Corp.|location=Millersville, MD|oclc=45763678}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Association of American Law Schools. Annual Meeting|last2=Association of American Law Schools, section on Student Services|title=Treading the waters : public interest values - law school and beyond|date=2001|url=https://www.worldcat.org|publisher=Recorded Resources Corp.|location=Millersville, MD|oclc=45753904}}</ref> Upon his departure in September 2009,<ref name=\":0\" /> Williams left behind a [[City University of New York]] campus in [[Harlem, New York]], where more than one-third of the students are [[Hispanic]], and nearly 30-percent are [[African people|African]] or [[African American]], and half are born outside of the [[United States of America]]. In total, ninety languages are spoken on campus.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rieselman|first1=Deborah|title=New UC president Gregory Williams embraces diversity|url=http://magazine.uc.edu/issues/1009/president.html|website=magazine.uc.edu|publisher=University of Cincinnati}}</ref>\n\nWilliams began his tenure as president of the [[University of Cincinnati]] on November 1, 2009.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Foderaro|first1=Lisa W.|title=City College President Leaving for Cincinnati|url=http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com|work=The New York Times|date=September 9, 2009}}</ref> During William's first year in the office of president, he launched a strategic plan, UC2019 - Accelerating Our Transformation, which took its name from the university's upcoming bicentennial year.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Peale|first1=Cliff|title=UC set to name new president|url=http://magazine.uc.edu/editors_picks/recent_features/president.html|newspaper=Cincinnati Enquirer|date=September 8, 2009}}</ref> During his presidency at the [[University of Cincinnati]], enrollment reached an historic level; the university established a new health system.<ref>{{cite web|title=Office of the President, University of Cincinnati: Gregory H. Williams|url=https://www.uc.edu/president/the-office/former_presidents/williams.html|website=UC.edu|publisher=University of Cincinnati|accessdate=15 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Gregory H. Williams Chosen To Lead UC|url=http://www.uc.edu/foundation/news_events/press_releases/new_president.html|website=University of Cincinnati Foundation}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Five Graduates Receive Alumni Achievement Award|url=https://gwtoday.gwu.edu|website=GW Today|publisher=George Washington University|accessdate=September 24, 2015}}</ref> In 2012, Williams resigned from the position of president, citing personal reasons.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Stripling|first1=Jack|title=U. of Cincinnati President Resigns Abruptly, Citing 'Personal Reasons'|url=http://chronicle.com/article/U-of-Cincinnati-President/133898/|website=The Chronicle of Higher Education|date=August 21, 2012}}</ref> That same year, Williams chaired the search for a new commissioner of the [[Big East Conference]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Weiss|first1=Dick|title=John Marinatto resigns as commissioner of Big East Conference, Joseph A. Bailey III takes over on interim basis|url=http://www.nydailynews.com|newspaper=NY Daily News|date=May 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Professional recognition===\nWilliams has been recognized for his contributions in scholarship, academic leadership, and fundraising. In 1998, [[President Bill Clinton]] invited Williams to join the United States President's Call to Action to promote [[Cultural diversity|diversity]] and [[pro bono]] legal services. The following year, Williams was selected by the National Association of Public Interest Law (NAPIL) as Dean of the Year. That same year, the [[National Bar Association]] awarded Williams the A. Leon Higginbotham Jr. Award for Contributions to the Preservation of Human and Civil Rights.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Grofman|first1=Bernard|last2=Federal Judicial Center|title=Legacies of the 1964 Civil Rights Act : [...papers given at a 1994 conference..., held at the Federal Judicial Center]|date=2000|publisher=University Press of Virginia|location=Charlottesville, Va.|isbn=0813919207|page=xiii|url=http://www.worldcat.org}}</ref>\n\nNotably, he received the [[National Bar Association]]'s A. Leon Higginbotham Jr. Award for Outstanding Contributions to the Preservation of Human and Civil Rights (1999); Governor's Tribute to African-American Leaders of Excellence in State Service (2004) from New York Governor [[George Pataki]]; [[Austrian Decoration for Science and Art]] in the Division of for Science and Art, [[Vienna, Austria]] (2006); Proclamation of Dr. Gregory Howard Williams Day and Honorary Mayor-President by Mayor [[Kip Holden]] of [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana]] (2006); Key to the City from Mayor Daniel Canan of [[Muncie, Indiana]] (2006);<ref>{{cite journal|title=Ex- Muncie resident visits alma mater to talk about his life on the Color Line|date=March 16, 2006|volume=16|issue=5|url=https://newspapers.library.in.gov/cgi-bin/indiana?a=d&d=BALLMT20060316-01.1.5|publisher=The Muncie Times}}</ref> [[Langston Hughes]] Award from [[The City College of New York]] for contributions to the Arts and Letters (2009); Bridges for a Just Community Distinguished Service Citation (2012); and [[George Washington University]] Law School Distinguished Alumni Achievement Award (2015).<ref>{{cite web|title=Two Graduates Receive Alumni Achievement Award|url=https://www.law.gwu.edu|publisher=George Washington University|accessdate=December 30, 2015}}</ref> Williams is also honored by the Gregory H. Williams Chair in Civil Rights & Civil Liberties of the [[Moritz College of Law]] at [[Ohio State University]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Is Perception Blind: Understanding Breakthrough Mind Science Research on Racial and Other Biases|url=http://blankfoundation.org/racial-bias|website=blankfoundation.org|publisher=The Arthur M. Blank Family Foundation}}</ref>\n\nWilliams also received honorary doctorate degrees from the [[California Western School of Law]] (1997), [[Ball State University]] (1999),<ref>{{cite web|title=Conferment of Honorary Degrees: Gregory H. Williams, Doctor of Humanities|url=https://cms.bsu.edu/-/media/WWW/DepartmentalContent/GradSchool/pdfs/Grad%20Catalog/3348%20cat%20p%20351%20355.pdf|website=Ball State University|date=May 8, 1999}}</ref> [[College of Wooster]] (2000), [[New York Law School]] (2009),<ref>{{cite web|title=President of The City College of New York, Gregory H. Williams, to Speak at New York Law School Commencement May 15|url=http://www.nyls.edu/news-and-events/president-of-the-city-college-of-new-york-gregory-h-williams-to-speak-at-new-york-law-school-commencement-may-15/|website=nyls.edu|publisher=New York Law School}}</ref> [[Skidmore College]] (2010),<ref>{{cite web|title=Skidmore College to honor Clive Gillinson, Gwen Ifill, Gregory Howard Williams with honorary degrees at 99th commencement|url=http://www.saratogian.com/article/ST/20100510/NEWS/305109985|website=Saratogian News|publisher=The Saratogian|date=May 10, 2010}}</ref> and [[Columbia University]] (2016).<ref>{{cite web|title=Racial Passing and Masquerade in American Culture from the Mid-Nineteenth Century|url=http://english.columbia.edu/racial-passing-and-masquerade-american-culture-mid-nineteenth-century|website=Department of English and Comparative Literature|publisher=Columbia University|accessdate=14 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Corporate and public boards ==\n*Independent Trustee, Franklin Templeton, Franklin Managed Trust and Value Investors Trust, [[San Mateo, California]], 2008- <ref>{{cite web|title=Gregory H. Williams Ph.D., J.D.|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=49645410&privcapId=4297720|website=bloomberg.com}}</ref>\n*Finance Committee, Nominations Committee, Independent Director, Urban America Fund II, 2005 -\n*Chair, Iowa Law Enforcement Academy Council, 1982\u201383, 1985, Vice-Chairperson, 1981\u201382,1984\u201385; Member, 1980\u201385, appointed by the Governor of Iowa for two terms, and confirmed by [[Iowa State Senate]]\n*Chair, Iowa Advisory Committee to the [[United States Commission on Civil Rights]], 1983\u20131985; Member 1978-1988\n\n== Publications ==\nWilliams published autobiography, Life on the Color Line: The True Story of a White Boy Who Discovered He Was Black - was awarded the 1995 [[Los Angeles Times]] Book of the Year.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Los Angeles Times Book Prizes 1995|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1995-09-24/books/bk-49312_1_los-angeles-times-book|newspaper=The Los Angeles Times|date=September 24, 1995}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Williams|first1=Gregory H.|title=A Line Through a Nation's Soul|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2003/oct/29/opinion/oe-williams29|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=October 29, 2003}}</ref> The term the [[Color line (civil rights issue)|color line]], a reference to [[racial segregation]], was famously used in an article \"The Color Line\" by [[Frederick Douglass]], published in the [[North American Review]] (NAR) in 1881, and repeated by [[W. E. B. Du Bois]], in his book [[The Souls of Black Folk]], in 1903.\n\nWilliams' book is a reflection on his life growing up as the son of a white mother and a father who passed for white and identified himself as [[Italian American]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Haynes|first1=Monica L.|title=Passing: How posing as white became a choice for many black Americans|url=http://old.post-gazette.com/lifestyle/20031026stain1026fnp2.asp|website=post-gazette.com|publisher=PG Publishing Co., Inc.|accessdate=October 26, 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Delgado|first1=Richard|last2=Stefancic|first2=Jean|title=Critical white studies : looking behind the mirror|date=1997|publisher=Temple University Press|location=Philadelphia, PA|isbn=9781439901519|pages=493\u2013498|url=http://www.worldcat.org}}</ref> At 10-years-old, Williams moved from his home in Virginia to [[Indiana]], where he learned his father was [[African-American]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Metress|first1=Christopher|title=The lynching of Emmett Till : a documentary narrative|date=2002|publisher=University of Virginia Press|location=Charlottesville, Virginia|isbn=081392121X|pages=Chapter 5|url=https://archive.org/details/lynchingofemmett00chri}}</ref>\n\nWilliams' book ''Life on the Color Line'' was awarded the [[Gustavus Myers Outstanding Book Awards|Outstanding Book on the Subject of Human Rights in North America]] by the [[Gustavus Myers Center for Human Rights]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news-releases.uiowa.edu/2002/december/1211pres-candidate.html|title=Gregory Williams, former UI law professor, is first on-campus candidate for UI president|last1=Parrott|first1=Steve|date=December 11, 2002|website=The University of Iowa News Service|publisher=University of Iowa}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=A multicultural reader. Collection two|date=2008|publisher=Perfection Learning Corporation|location=Logan, Iowa|isbn=9780789171498|pages=462 pages : illustrations ; 23 cm|edition=2nd|url=https://www.worldcat.org|format=Many voices literature series}}</ref> Williams has been a featured author on [[Dateline NBC]], [[Larry King Live]], [[The Oprah Winfrey Show]], [[Nightline]], [[NPR]], and public lectures.<ref>{{cite web|title=What's New : Dr. Williams Program|url=http://www.cincinnatilibrary.org/news/2011/gregorywilliams.html|website=cincinnatilibrary.org|publisher=The Public Library of Cincinnati and Hamilton County}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=CI to host Author Gregory H. Williams|url=http://www.csuci.edu/news/releases/2011-authorgregorywilliams.htm|website=csuci.edu|publisher=California State University Channel Islands}}</ref> His book has been cited in [[academic journals]]<ref>{{cite book|last1=Williams|first1=Tyrone|title=Masterplots II. / African American literature 4 Pos - Z|date=2009|publisher=Salem Press|location=Pasadena, Calif.|isbn=9781587654428|pages=S. LXXVII - XCI, S. 1557\u20132046|edition=1st|url=https://www.worldcat.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Today's best nonfiction : Robert Timberg; Gregory Howard Williams; Andrew A Rooney; Jeffrey Good; Susan Goreck;|journal=Reader's Digest|date=1995|volume=36|issue=1|pages=573 pages : illustrations, portraits ; 24 cm|url=https://www.worldcat.org|publisher=Readers Digest Association|location=Pleasantville, New York}}</ref> and [[syllabus]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Living In The Shadow Of Family Secrets|url=https://www.npr.org/2011/02/03/133467029/Living-In-The-Shadow-Of-Family-Secrets|website=npr.org|publisher=National Public Radio|accessdate=February 3, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Books===\n* Williams, G. H. (1995, 1999, 2014). ''Life On The color line: The true story of a white boy who discovered he was black''. New York, N.Y: Dutton.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Williams|first1=Gregory Howard|title=Life on the color line : the true story of a white boy who discovered he was black|date=1995|publisher=Dutton|location=New York|isbn=9780525938507|url=https://archive.org/details/lifeoncolorlinet00will}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Williams|first1=Gregory|title=Life on the color line: The true story of a white boy who discovered he was black|date=1999|publisher=Plume|location=New York|isbn=0613035364|edition=Special Ball State University}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Williams|first1=Gregory Howard|title=Life on the color line : the true story of a white boy who discovered he was black|date=2014|publisher=Plume|location=New York|isbn=9781440673337}}</ref>\n* Williams, G. H. (1986). ''The Iowa guide to search and seizure''. Iowa City: University of Iowa.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Williams|first1=Gregory Howard|title=The Iowa guide to search and seizure|date=1986|publisher=University of Iowa|isbn=0874140447}}</ref>\n* Williams, G. H. (1984). ''The law and politics of police discretion''. Westport, Connecticut: Greenwood Press.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Williams|first1=Gregory Howard|title=The law and politics of police discretion|date=1984|publisher=Greenwood Press|location=Westport, Conn.|isbn=0313240701}}</ref>\n*\n\n===Articles and other contributory publications===\n*Williams, Gregory H. (1998) \"Transforming the Powerless to the Powerful: the public responsibility of law school.\" 1, New Mexico Law Review Journal, 28, 17 pages.<ref>{{cite journal|title=New Mexico Law Review|volume=28|issue=1|pages=1\u201318|url=http://lawschool.unm.edu/nmlr/volumes/28/1/01_williams_transforming.pdf|publisher=University of New Mexico Law|location=Albuquerdue, New Mexico}}</ref>\n*Williams, Gregory H. (1993) \"Controlling the Use of Non-Deadly Force: Policy and Practice,\" 10 Harvard Black Letter Journal 79, 25 pages.\n*Williams, Gregory H. (1992) \"Teaching Criminal Law: 'Objectivity' in Black and White,\" 9 Harvard Blackletter Journal 27, 16 pages.\n*Williams, Gregory H. (1991) \"The Supreme Court and Broken Promises: The Gradual but Continual Erosion of Terry v. Ohio,\" Criminal Justice Symposium, 34 Howard Law Journal 567, 22 pages.\n*Williams, Gregory H. (1990) \"America's Drug Policy: Who are the Addicts?\" 75 Iowa Law Review 1119, 15 pages.\n*Williams, Gregory H. (1990) \"Good Government by Prosecutorial Decree: The Use and Abuse of Mail Fraud,\" 32 Arizona Law Review. 1, 35 pages.\n*Williams, Gregory H. (1989) \"Police Discretion: A Comparative Perspective.\" 64 Indiana Law Journal 873, 33 pages.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Williams|first1=Gregory H.|title=Police Discretion: A Comparative Perspective|url=http://www.repository.law.indiana.edu/ilj/vol64/iss4/3|website=Indiana Law Journal|accessdate=11 June 2016}}</ref>\n*Williams, Gregory H. (1987) \"Where is Freedom: Federal or State Constitutions?\" 30 Howard Law Journal 799, 7 pages.\n*Williams, Gregory H. (1989) \"Police in the Dock: Law or Fact?\" Criminal Law Review 719, 7 pages.\n*Williams, Gregory H., et al. (1986). Discrecin\u0324, justicia y democracia: Una perspectiva de la polt\u0315ica pb\ufe22lica. Mx\u030cico: Noema.\n*Williams, Gregory H. (1984) \"Police Rulemaking Revisited: Some New Thoughts on an Old Problem.\" 47 Law and Contemporary Problems 123, 61 pages.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Williams|first1=Gregory Howard|editor1-last=Allen|editor1-first=Ronald J|title=Police Rulemaking Revisited: Some New Thoughts on an Old Problem|journal=47|date=October 1, 1984|volume=4|pages=312|series=Law and contemporary problems|publisher=Duke University School of Law|location=Durham, N.C.|oclc=908031874}}</ref>\n*Williams, Gregory H. (1984) \"Use of Citations in Lieu of Custodial Arrest.\" Report of the Iowa Law Enforcement Academy Council to the Iowa General Assembly.\n*Williams, Gregory H. (1983) \"Police Discretion: The Institutional Dilemma--Who Is In Charge?\" 68 Iowa Law Review 431, 63 pages.\n\n===Video===\n* Williams, G. H., Brown, T., Smith, K., & Ashby, W. (2006). The man who is black and white\u2014not half white. New York: Tony Brown Productions Inc.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Williams|first1=Gregory Howard|last2=Brown, (Journalist)|first2=Tony|last3=Smith|first3=Karen|last4=Ashby|first4=Wally|title=The man who is black and white -- not half white|date=2006|url=http://www.worldcat.org|publisher=Tony Brown Productions Inc.|location=New York|language=English|oclc=881547619}}</ref>\n\n== Personal Life ==\nWilliams married Sara Catherine Whitney, (m. August 29, 1969). Their children are Natalia Dora, Zachary Benjamin, Anthony B\u00eead\u00eemir, Carlos Gregory.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stephen|first1=Stratton|date=March 3, 1995|title=Williams, Gregory 1943\u2014|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1G2-2871300068.html|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|issue=Contemporary Black Biography|pages=1\u20134}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}} \n{{s-aca}}\n{{succession box|title=[[University of Cincinnati|President of University of Cincinnati]]|before=[[Nancy Zimpher]]|after=[[Santa J. Ono]]|years=2009 &ndash; 2012}}\n{{succession box|title=[[City College of New York|President of City College of New York]]|before=[[Yolanda T. Moses]]|after=Robert \"Buzz\" Paaswell, (interim)|years=2001 &ndash; 2009}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Moritz College of Law|Dean of Moritz College of Law]] | before= [[Francis X. Beytagh]] | years=1993-2001 | after=[[Nancy H. Rogers]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{University of Cincinnati presidents}}\n{{City College of New York presidents}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Williams, Gregory H.}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Cincinnati faculty]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the University of Cincinnati]]\n[[Category:Presidents of City College of New York]]\n[[Category:George Washington University Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:African-American academics]]\n[[Category:Law schools in Ohio]]\n[[Category:Iowa State University faculty]]\n[[Category:Ohio State University faculty]]\n[[Category:Moritz College of Law faculty]]\n[[Category:Law school deans]]\n[[Category:Mercy College (New York) alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix   = \n|name               = Gregory Howard Williams\n|honorific-suffix   =\n|image              =\n|imagesize          =\n|smallimage         = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n|alt                =\n|caption            =\n|office             = 28th [[University of Cincinnati|President of University of Cincinnati]]\n|term_start         = 2009\n|term_end           = 2012\n|predecessor        = [[Nancy L. Zimpher]]\n|successor          = [[Santa J. Ono]]\n|order2             =\n|office2            = 11th President of [[the City College of New York]]\n|term_start2        = 2001\n|term_end2          = 2009\n|predecessor2       = Stanford A. Roman Jr., interim; [[Yolanda T. Moses]], President\n|successor2         = Robert \"Buzz\" Paaswell, interim; [[Lisa Staiano-Coico]], President\n| office3           = 17th Dean of [[Moritz College of Law]]\n| term_start3       = 1993\n| term_end3         = 2001\n| predecessor3      = [[Francis X. Beytagh]]\n| successor3        = [[Nancy H. Rogers]]\n| alma_mater        = [[George Washington University]]\n}}\n\n'''Gregory Howard Williams''' is a scholar, attorney, law school professor, author, and formerly the 27th President of the [[University of Cincinnati]] (2009 to 2012)<ref>{{cite web|title=Dr. Gregory H. Williams|url=https://cityclub.org|website=The City Club of Clevland|accessdate=11 June 2016}}</ref> and the 11th President of [[the City College of New York]] (2001 - 2009).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Simon|first1=Ellis|title=CCNY President DR. Gregory H. Williams Resigns To Become President Of University Of Cincinnati|url=https://www.ccny.cuny.edu/news/CCNY-PRESIDENT-GREGORY-WILLIAMS-RESIGNS-TO-BECOME-PRESIDENT-OF-UNIVERSITY-OF-CINCINNATI|website=The City College of New York|publisher=City University of New York|date=September 9, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Holmes|first1=Marie|title=College President Series: Gregory H. Williams: President, City College|url=http://www.educationupdate.com/archives/2002/oct02/issue/col-collegepres.htm|publisher=Education Update, Inc.|date=October 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Mabunda|first1=L Mpho|last2=Phelps|first2=Shirelle|title=Contemporary Black biography. Volume 11 : profiles from the international Black community|date=1996|publisher=Gale Research Inc.|location=Detroit, Mich|isbn=9781414435398|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education ==\nGregory Howard Williams was born on November 12, 1943, in [[Muncie, Indiana]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thehistorymakers.org/biography/gregory-h-williams-41|title=Gregory H. Williams {{!}} The HistoryMakers|website=www.thehistorymakers.org|language=en|access-date=2018-02-11}}</ref> He was the son of James Anthony, a businessman, and Mary, a homemaker. He grew up in [[Gum Spring, Virginia]], until his parents separated, and his father lost his business. At the age of ten years old, Williams and his brother moved to [[Muncie, Indiana]]<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Moten-Foster |display-authors=etal |first1=Bea|authorlink=Bea Moten-Foster|title=Gregory Howard Williams|journal=Muncie Times|date=May 5, 2002|volume=11|issue=9|url=https://www.worldcat.org|publisher=The Muncie Times|location=Muncie, Indiana}}</ref> where his father had family, and he first became aware of his father's [[African American]] heritage.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Perry|first1=Michael|title=UC's new president has a powerful story to tell|url=http://www.gobearcats.com/sports/ucats/spec-rel/120809aag.html|website=gobearcats.com|publisher=CBS Interactive|date=December 8, 2009}}</ref> Despite a period of confusion about his own identity, Williams embraced his father's passion for education.<ref>{{cite web|title=The History Makers: The Nation's Largest African American Oral History Collection|url=http://www.thehistorymakers.com|accessdate=May 16, 2007}}</ref>\n\nWilliams earned a bachelor of arts degree from [[Ball State University]] in 1966, where he paid tuition by earning money as a [[deputy sheriff]] in the Delaware County Sheriff's Department in [[Muncie, Indiana]], from 1963 to 1966. Between 1966 and 1970, Williams taught classes in Virginia state government and history George Mason Junior \u2013 Senior High School in [[Falls Church, Virginia]]. In 1969, he earned a master's degree in government and politics from [[University of Maryland]]. Williams earned a J.D. from [[George Washington University]] in 1971. From 1971 to 1973, Williams was a legislative assistant to Senator [[Vance Hartke]] (D-Indiana) of the [[United States Senate]], [[Washington, D.C.]]. In 1977, Williams earned a master's degree in political science, and in 1982, a doctorate in political science, both from [[George Washington University]] with a thesis \"Legal and political problems of police discretion\".<ref>{{cite thesis|last1=Williams|first1=Gregory Howard|title=Legal and political problems of police discretion|date=1982|degree=Ph.D.|publisher=George Washington University|oclc=10315748}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Rieselman|first1=Deborah|title=New UC president Gregory Williams embraces diversity|url=http://magazine.uc.edu/issues/1009/president.html|website=UC Magazine|publisher=University of Cincinnati}}</ref> He also earned an MBA from [[Mercy College (New York)]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://educationupdate.com/homeroom/2017/03/mercy-college.html#.WQt1fegrKUk|title=Mercy College Hosts 36th Annual Mercy College Trustees' Scholarship Dinner - Homeroom|website=educationupdate.com|access-date=2019-10-30}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nWilliams joined the [[University of Iowa]] Law faculty in 1977, where he taught [[criminal law]], [[criminal procedure]], and [[legislation]]. Williams was faculty scholar from 1990 to 1993. At Iowa, Williams served as [[Associate Dean]] of the Law School, from 1977 to 1993, where he oversaw admissions, financial aid, student and faculty recruitment, and student support, and he served as Associate Vice President of Academic Affairs from 1991-93.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gregory H.Williams|url=http://library.law.uiowa.edu|website=University of Iowa Law Library|publisher=The University of Iowa|accessdate=11 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1975 to 1977, he consulted to the Foreign Lawyer Training Program in [[Washington, DC]]. He was a member of the Iowa State Advisory Commission to the [[United States Civil Rights Commission]] from 1978 to 1988, and a member of the Iowa Law Enforcement Academy Council from 1979 to 1985.<ref>{{cite web|title=Williams, Gregory 1943|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com|website=Encyclopedia.com|accessdate=11 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nWilliams was appointed visiting professor on faculty of law at [[Durham University]], [[Durham, England]], from 1984 to 1986, and visiting scholar at [[Selwyn College, Cambridge|Selwyn College]] at [[Cambridge University]], [[Cambridge, England]], from 1986 to 1987.\n\nFrom 1991 to 1993, he held the position of Associate Vice-President for Academic Affairs at the [[University of Iowa]] in [[Iowa City, Iowa]]. From 1993 to 2001, Williams held the positions of Carter Kissell Professor of Law and Dean of the Michael E. [[Moritz College of Law]] at [[Ohio State University]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Arenson|first1=Karen W.|title=Ohio Law School Dean Is Named As New President of City College|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/03/27/nyregion/ohio-law-school-dean-is-named-as-new-president-of-city-college.html|newspaper=NY Times|date=March 27, 2001}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Lassiter|first1=Luke E|title=The other side of Middletown : exploring Muncie's African American community|date=2004|publisher=AltaMira Press|location=Walnut Creek, CA|isbn=0759104832|page=41|url=http://www.worldcat.org}}</ref> While Dean, the size of the faculty increased by 40 percent, the number of named chairs and professorships doubled, and $25 million was raised from alumni of approximately 7,000 graduates.<ref>{{cite web|title=Prominent Law School Dean Gregory H. Williams Named City College President|url=http://www1.cuny.edu/mu/forum/2001/03/26/prominent-law-school-dean-gregory-h-williams-named-city-college-president/|website=CUNY|publisher=The City University of New York|date=March 26, 2001}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Rose|first1=Derek|last2=Hutchinson|first2=Bill|title=11th CCNY Prez Named \u2014 Ohio law school dean, author to head school|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/11th-ccny-prez-named-ohio-law-school-dean-author-head-school-article-1.914545|work=Daily News|date=March 27, 2001}}</ref>\n\n===College presidencies===\nIn 2001, Williams was appointed the 11th President of [[the City College of New York]] - the flagship campus of the [[City University of New York]] system. His appointment followed his tenure as a law school dean at [[Ohio State]] since 1993, where Williams taught courses in criminal law, he raised $25 million and oversaw the increase of the school's endowment by about 50 percent.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Arenson|first1=Karen W.|title=2 Law School Deans Are Finalists for City College Presidency|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/03/18/nyregion/2-law-school-deans-are-finalists-for-city-college-presidency.html|work=The New York Times|date=March 18, 2001}}</ref> During his tenure at Ohio State, Williams also served as the president of the Association of American Law Schools and his autobiographical book, ''Life on the Color Line: The True Story of a White Boy Who Discovered He Was Black'', (Dutton, 1995) won the 1995 Los Angeles Times Book Award.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Arenson|first1=Karen W.|title=The President Of City College May Leave Post|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/12/12/nyregion/the-president-of-city-college-may-leave-post.html|work=The New York Times|date=December 12, 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Graff|first1=E.|title=Being Black and White|url=http://prospect.org/article/being-black-and-white|website=The American Prospect|date=December 10, 2001}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.cuny.edu/events/cunymatters/2001_summer/collegepresidency.html|title=Midwestern Law School Dean Assumes City College Presidency|last=|first=|date=|website=CUNY Matters|publisher=City University of New Yorkj|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nUnder Williams' presidency of [[the City College of New York]], enrollment increased by 60&nbsp;percent and academic standards improved significantly; nearly 90&nbsp;percent of the student body continue to represent racial minority groups.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|last1=Foderaro|first1=Lisa W.|title=President of City College Is Taking Helm at Cincinnati|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/10/nyregion/10ccny.html|newspaper=NY Times|date=September 9, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Rivers|first1=Voza|last2=Williams|first2=Lloyd A|title=Forever Harlem: Celebrating America's Most Diverse Community|date=2006|publisher=Sports Pub.|location=Champaign, Ill.|isbn=9781596702066|page=256|url=http://www.worldcat.org}}</ref> Williams successfully oversaw the first [[capital campaign]] at City College,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mwamba|first1=Jay|title=CCNY'S 160th Commencement Set For June 1; President Gregory Williams To Address Graduates|url=http://www1.cuny.edu/mu/forum/2006/05/25/ccnys-160th-commencement-set-for-june-1-president-gregory-williams-to-address-graduates/|website=City College of New York|publisher=City University of New York|date=May 25, 2006}}</ref> raising more than $230 million and effectively establishing a culture of philanthropy, and more than doubled City College's research funding.\n\nDuring his tenure as president of [[the City College of New York]], Williams served as Chair of the Commission on Access, Diversity, and Excellence (CADE) of the [[Association of Public and Land-grant Universities]]. Williams moderated and presented at the 2001 Association of American Law Schools annual meeting.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Chander|first1=Anupam|last2=Coates|first2=John C|last3=Association of American Law Schools|title=AALS scholarly paper presentation|date=2001|url=https://www.worldcat.org|publisher=Recorded Resources Corp.|location=Millersville, MD|oclc=45763678}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Association of American Law Schools. Annual Meeting|last2=Association of American Law Schools, section on Student Services|title=Treading the waters : public interest values - law school and beyond|date=2001|url=https://www.worldcat.org|publisher=Recorded Resources Corp.|location=Millersville, MD|oclc=45753904}}</ref> Upon his departure in September 2009,<ref name=\":0\" /> Williams left behind a [[City University of New York]] campus in [[Harlem, New York]], where more than one-third of the students are [[Hispanic]], and nearly 30-percent are [[African people|African]] or [[African American]], and half are born outside of the [[United States of America]]. In total, ninety languages are spoken on campus.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rieselman|first1=Deborah|title=New UC president Gregory Williams embraces diversity|url=http://magazine.uc.edu/issues/1009/president.html|website=magazine.uc.edu|publisher=University of Cincinnati}}</ref>\n\nWilliams began his tenure as president of the [[University of Cincinnati]] on November 1, 2009.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Foderaro|first1=Lisa W.|title=City College President Leaving for Cincinnati|url=http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com|work=The New York Times|date=September 9, 2009}}</ref> During William's first year in the office of president, he launched a strategic plan, UC2019 - Accelerating Our Transformation, which took its name from the university's upcoming bicentennial year.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Peale|first1=Cliff|title=UC set to name new president|url=http://magazine.uc.edu/editors_picks/recent_features/president.html|newspaper=Cincinnati Enquirer|date=September 8, 2009}}</ref> During his presidency at the [[University of Cincinnati]], enrollment reached an historic level; the university established a new health system.<ref>{{cite web|title=Office of the President, University of Cincinnati: Gregory H. Williams|url=https://www.uc.edu/president/the-office/former_presidents/williams.html|website=UC.edu|publisher=University of Cincinnati|accessdate=15 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Gregory H. Williams Chosen To Lead UC|url=http://www.uc.edu/foundation/news_events/press_releases/new_president.html|website=University of Cincinnati Foundation}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Five Graduates Receive Alumni Achievement Award|url=https://gwtoday.gwu.edu|website=GW Today|publisher=George Washington University|accessdate=September 24, 2015}}</ref> In 2012, Williams resigned from the position of president, citing personal reasons.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Stripling|first1=Jack|title=U. of Cincinnati President Resigns Abruptly, Citing 'Personal Reasons'|url=http://chronicle.com/article/U-of-Cincinnati-President/133898/|website=The Chronicle of Higher Education|date=August 21, 2012}}</ref> That same year, Williams chaired the search for a new commissioner of the [[Big East Conference]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Weiss|first1=Dick|title=John Marinatto resigns as commissioner of Big East Conference, Joseph A. Bailey III takes over on interim basis|url=http://www.nydailynews.com|newspaper=NY Daily News|date=May 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Professional recognition===\nWilliams has been recognized for his contributions in scholarship, academic leadership, and fundraising. In 1998, [[President Bill Clinton]] invited Williams to join the United States President's Call to Action to promote [[Cultural diversity|diversity]] and [[pro bono]] legal services. The following year, Williams was selected by the National Association of Public Interest Law (NAPIL) as Dean of the Year. That same year, the [[National Bar Association]] awarded Williams the A. Leon Higginbotham Jr. Award for Contributions to the Preservation of Human and Civil Rights.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Grofman|first1=Bernard|last2=Federal Judicial Center|title=Legacies of the 1964 Civil Rights Act : [...papers given at a 1994 conference..., held at the Federal Judicial Center]|date=2000|publisher=University Press of Virginia|location=Charlottesville, Va.|isbn=0813919207|page=xiii|url=http://www.worldcat.org}}</ref>\n\nNotably, he received the [[National Bar Association]]'s A. Leon Higginbotham Jr. Award for Outstanding Contributions to the Preservation of Human and Civil Rights (1999); Governor's Tribute to African-American Leaders of Excellence in State Service (2004) from New York Governor [[George Pataki]]; [[Austrian Decoration for Science and Art]] in the Division of for Science and Art, [[Vienna, Austria]] (2006); Proclamation of Dr. Gregory Howard Williams Day and Honorary Mayor-President by Mayor [[Kip Holden]] of [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana]] (2006); Key to the City from Mayor Daniel Canan of [[Muncie, Indiana]] (2006);<ref>{{cite journal|title=Ex- Muncie resident visits alma mater to talk about his life on the Color Line|date=March 16, 2006|volume=16|issue=5|url=https://newspapers.library.in.gov/cgi-bin/indiana?a=d&d=BALLMT20060316-01.1.5|publisher=The Muncie Times}}</ref> [[Langston Hughes]] Award from [[The City College of New York]] for contributions to the Arts and Letters (2009); Bridges for a Just Community Distinguished Service Citation (2012); and [[George Washington University]] Law School Distinguished Alumni Achievement Award (2015).<ref>{{cite web|title=Two Graduates Receive Alumni Achievement Award|url=https://www.law.gwu.edu|publisher=George Washington University|accessdate=December 30, 2015}}</ref> Williams is also honored by the Gregory H. Williams Chair in Civil Rights & Civil Liberties of the [[Moritz College of Law]] at [[Ohio State University]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Is Perception Blind: Understanding Breakthrough Mind Science Research on Racial and Other Biases|url=http://blankfoundation.org/racial-bias|website=blankfoundation.org|publisher=The Arthur M. Blank Family Foundation}}</ref>\n\nWilliams also received honorary doctorate degrees from the [[California Western School of Law]] (1997), [[Ball State University]] (1999),<ref>{{cite web|title=Conferment of Honorary Degrees: Gregory H. Williams, Doctor of Humanities|url=https://cms.bsu.edu/-/media/WWW/DepartmentalContent/GradSchool/pdfs/Grad%20Catalog/3348%20cat%20p%20351%20355.pdf|website=Ball State University|date=May 8, 1999}}</ref> [[College of Wooster]] (2000), [[New York Law School]] (2009),<ref>{{cite web|title=President of The City College of New York, Gregory H. Williams, to Speak at New York Law School Commencement May 15|url=http://www.nyls.edu/news-and-events/president-of-the-city-college-of-new-york-gregory-h-williams-to-speak-at-new-york-law-school-commencement-may-15/|website=nyls.edu|publisher=New York Law School}}</ref> [[Skidmore College]] (2010),<ref>{{cite web|title=Skidmore College to honor Clive Gillinson, Gwen Ifill, Gregory Howard Williams with honorary degrees at 99th commencement|url=http://www.saratogian.com/article/ST/20100510/NEWS/305109985|website=Saratogian News|publisher=The Saratogian|date=May 10, 2010}}</ref> and [[Columbia University]] (2016).<ref>{{cite web|title=Racial Passing and Masquerade in American Culture from the Mid-Nineteenth Century|url=http://english.columbia.edu/racial-passing-and-masquerade-american-culture-mid-nineteenth-century|website=Department of English and Comparative Literature|publisher=Columbia University|accessdate=14 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Corporate and public boards ==\n*Independent Trustee, Franklin Templeton, Franklin Managed Trust and Value Investors Trust, [[San Mateo, California]], 2008- <ref>{{cite web|title=Gregory H. Williams Ph.D., J.D.|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=49645410&privcapId=4297720|website=bloomberg.com}}</ref>\n*Finance Committee, Nominations Committee, Independent Director, Urban America Fund II, 2005 -\n*Chair, Iowa Law Enforcement Academy Council, 1982\u201383, 1985, Vice-Chairperson, 1981\u201382,1984\u201385; Member, 1980-85, appointed by the Governor of Iowa for two terms, and confirmed by [[Iowa State Senate]]\n*Chair, Iowa Advisory Committee to the [[United States Commission on Civil Rights]], 1983-1985; Member 1978-1988\n\n== Publications ==\nWilliams published autobiography, Life on the Color Line: The True Story of a White Boy Who Discovered He Was Black - was awarded the 1995 [[Los Angeles Times]] Book of the Year.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Los Angeles Times Book Prizes 1995|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1995-09-24/books/bk-49312_1_los-angeles-times-book|newspaper=The Los Angeles Times|date=September 24, 1995}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Williams|first1=Gregory H.|title=A Line Through a Nation's Soul|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2003/oct/29/opinion/oe-williams29|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=October 29, 2003}}</ref> The term the [[Color line (civil rights issue)|color line]], a reference to [[racial segregation]], was famously used in an article \"The Color Line\" by [[Frederick Douglass]], published in the [[North American Review]] (NAR) in 1881, and repeated by [[W. E. B. Du Bois]], in his book [[The Souls of Black Folk]], in 1903.\n\nWilliams' book is a reflection on his life growing up as the son of a white mother and a father who passed for white and identified himself as [[Italian American]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Haynes|first1=Monica L.|title=Passing: How posing as white became a choice for many black Americans|url=http://old.post-gazette.com/lifestyle/20031026stain1026fnp2.asp|website=post-gazette.com|publisher=PG Publishing Co., Inc.|accessdate=October 26, 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Delgado|first1=Richard|last2=Stefancic|first2=Jean|title=Critical white studies : looking behind the mirror|date=1997|publisher=Temple University Press|location=Philadelphia, PA|isbn=9781439901519|pages=493\u2013498|url=http://www.worldcat.org}}</ref> At 10-years-old, Williams moved from his home in Virginia to [[Indiana]], where he learned his father was [[African-American]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Metress|first1=Christopher|title=The lynching of Emmett Till : a documentary narrative|date=2002|publisher=University of Virginia Press|location=Charlottesville, Virginia|isbn=081392121X|pages=Chapter 5|url=https://archive.org/details/lynchingofemmett00chri}}</ref>\n\nWilliams' book ''Life on the Color Line'' was awarded the [[Gustavus Myers Outstanding Book Awards|Outstanding Book on the Subject of Human Rights in North America]] by the [[Gustavus Myers Center for Human Rights]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news-releases.uiowa.edu/2002/december/1211pres-candidate.html|title=Gregory Williams, former UI law professor, is first on-campus candidate for UI president|last1=Parrott|first1=Steve|date=December 11, 2002|website=The University of Iowa News Service|publisher=University of Iowa}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=A multicultural reader. Collection two|date=2008|publisher=Perfection Learning Corporation|location=Logan, Iowa|isbn=9780789171498|pages=462 pages : illustrations ; 23 cm|edition=2nd|url=https://www.worldcat.org|format=Many voices literature series}}</ref> Williams has been a featured author on [[Dateline NBC]], [[Larry King Live]], [[The Oprah Winfrey Show]], [[Nightline]], [[NPR]], and public lectures.<ref>{{cite web|title=What's New : Dr. Williams Program|url=http://www.cincinnatilibrary.org/news/2011/gregorywilliams.html|website=cincinnatilibrary.org|publisher=The Public Library of Cincinnati and Hamilton County}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=CI to host Author Gregory H. Williams|url=http://www.csuci.edu/news/releases/2011-authorgregorywilliams.htm|website=csuci.edu|publisher=California State University Channel Islands}}</ref> His book has been cited in [[academic journals]]<ref>{{cite book|last1=Williams|first1=Tyrone|title=Masterplots II. / African American literature 4 Pos - Z|date=2009|publisher=Salem Press|location=Pasadena, Calif.|isbn=9781587654428|pages=S. LXXVII - XCI, S. 1557\u20132046|edition=1st|url=https://www.worldcat.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Today's best nonfiction : Robert Timberg; Gregory Howard Williams; Andrew A Rooney; Jeffrey Good; Susan Goreck;|journal=Reader's Digest|date=1995|volume=36|issue=1|pages=573 pages : illustrations, portraits ; 24 cm|url=https://www.worldcat.org|publisher=Readers Digest Association|location=Pleasantville, New York}}</ref> and [[syllabus]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Living In The Shadow Of Family Secrets|url=https://www.npr.org/2011/02/03/133467029/Living-In-The-Shadow-Of-Family-Secrets|website=npr.org|publisher=National Public Radio|accessdate=February 3, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Books===\n* Williams, G. H. (1995, 1999, 2014). ''Life On The color line: The true story of a white boy who discovered he was black''. New York, N.Y: Dutton.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Williams|first1=Gregory Howard|title=Life on the color line : the true story of a white boy who discovered he was black|date=1995|publisher=Dutton|location=New York|isbn=9780525938507|url=https://archive.org/details/lifeoncolorlinet00will}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Williams|first1=Gregory|title=Life on the color line: The true story of a white boy who discovered he was black|date=1999|publisher=Plume|location=New York|isbn=0613035364|edition=Special Ball State University}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Williams|first1=Gregory Howard|title=Life on the color line : the true story of a white boy who discovered he was black|date=2014|publisher=Plume|location=New York|isbn=9781440673337}}</ref>\n* Williams, G. H. (1986). ''The Iowa guide to search and seizure''. Iowa City: University of Iowa.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Williams|first1=Gregory Howard|title=The Iowa guide to search and seizure|date=1986|publisher=University of Iowa|isbn=0874140447}}</ref>\n* Williams, G. H. (1984). ''The law and politics of police discretion''. Westport, Connecticut: Greenwood Press.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Williams|first1=Gregory Howard|title=The law and politics of police discretion|date=1984|publisher=Greenwood Press|location=Westport, Conn.|isbn=0313240701}}</ref>\n*\n\n===Articles and other contributory publications===\n*Williams, Gregory H. (1998) \"Transforming the Powerless to the Powerful: the public responsibility of law school.\" 1, New Mexico Law Review Journal, 28, 17 pages.<ref>{{cite journal|title=New Mexico Law Review|volume=28|issue=1|pages=1\u201318|url=http://lawschool.unm.edu/nmlr/volumes/28/1/01_williams_transforming.pdf|publisher=University of New Mexico Law|location=Albuquerdue, New Mexico}}</ref>\n*Williams, Gregory H. (1993) \"Controlling the Use of Non-Deadly Force: Policy and Practice,\" 10 Harvard Black Letter Journal 79, 25 pages.\n*Williams, Gregory H. (1992) \"Teaching Criminal Law: 'Objectivity' in Black and White,\" 9 Harvard Blackletter Journal 27, 16 pages.\n*Williams, Gregory H. (1991) \"The Supreme Court and Broken Promises: The Gradual but Continual Erosion of Terry v. Ohio,\" Criminal Justice Symposium, 34 Howard Law Journal 567, 22 pages.\n*Williams, Gregory H. (1990) \"America's Drug Policy: Who are the Addicts?\" 75 Iowa Law Review 1119, 15 pages.\n*Williams, Gregory H. (1990) \"Good Government by Prosecutorial Decree: The Use and Abuse of Mail Fraud,\" 32 Arizona Law Review. 1, 35 pages.\n*Williams, Gregory H. (1989) \"Police Discretion: A Comparative Perspective.\" 64 Indiana Law Journal 873, 33 pages.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Williams|first1=Gregory H.|title=Police Discretion: A Comparative Perspective|url=http://www.repository.law.indiana.edu/ilj/vol64/iss4/3|website=Indiana Law Journal|accessdate=11 June 2016}}</ref>\n*Williams, Gregory H. (1987) \"Where is Freedom: Federal or State Constitutions?\" 30 Howard Law Journal 799, 7 pages.\n*Williams, Gregory H. (1989) \"Police in the Dock: Law or Fact?\" Criminal Law Review 719, 7 pages.\n*Williams, Gregory H., et al. (1986). Discrecin\u0324, justicia y democracia: Una perspectiva de la polt\u0315ica pb\ufe22lica. Mx\u030cico: Noema.\n*Williams, Gregory H. (1984) \"Police Rulemaking Revisited: Some New Thoughts on an Old Problem.\" 47 Law and Contemporary Problems 123, 61 pages.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Williams|first1=Gregory Howard|editor1-last=Allen|editor1-first=Ronald J|title=Police Rulemaking Revisited: Some New Thoughts on an Old Problem|journal=47|date=October 1, 1984|volume=4|pages=312|series=Law and contemporary problems|publisher=Duke University School of Law|location=Durham, N.C.|oclc=908031874}}</ref>\n*Williams, Gregory H. (1984) \"Use of Citations in Lieu of Custodial Arrest.\" Report of the Iowa Law Enforcement Academy Council to the Iowa General Assembly.\n*Williams, Gregory H. (1983) \"Police Discretion: The Institutional Dilemma--Who Is In Charge?\" 68 Iowa Law Review 431, 63 pages.\n\n===Video===\n* Williams, G. H., Brown, T., Smith, K., & Ashby, W. (2006). The man who is black and white\u2014not half white. New York: Tony Brown Productions Inc.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Williams|first1=Gregory Howard|last2=Brown, (Journalist)|first2=Tony|last3=Smith|first3=Karen|last4=Ashby|first4=Wally|title=The man who is black and white -- not half white|date=2006|url=http://www.worldcat.org|publisher=Tony Brown Productions Inc.|location=New York|language=English|oclc=881547619}}</ref>\n\n== Personal Life ==\nWilliams married Sara Catherine Whitney, (m. August 29, 1969). Their children are Natalia Dora, Zachary Benjamin, Anthony B\u00eead\u00eemir, Carlos Gregory.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stephen|first1=Stratton|date=March 3, 1995|title=Williams, Gregory 1943\u2014|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1G2-2871300068.html|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|issue=Contemporary Black Biography|pages=1\u20134}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}} \n{{s-aca}}\n{{succession box|title=[[University of Cincinnati|President of University of Cincinnati]]|before=[[Nancy Zimpher]]|after=[[Santa J. Ono]]|years=2009 &ndash; 2012}}\n{{succession box|title=[[City College of New York|President of City College of New York]]|before=[[Yolanda T. Moses]]|after=Robert \"Buzz\" Paaswell, (interim)|years=2001 &ndash; 2009}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Moritz College of Law|Dean of Moritz College of Law]] | before= [[Francis X. Beytagh]] | years=1993-2001 | after=[[Nancy H. Rogers]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{University of Cincinnati presidents}}\n{{City College of New York presidents}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Williams, Gregory H.}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Cincinnati faculty]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the University of Cincinnati]]\n[[Category:Presidents of City College of New York]]\n[[Category:George Washington University Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:African-American academics]]\n[[Category:Law schools in Ohio]]\n[[Category:Iowa State University faculty]]\n[[Category:Ohio State University faculty]]\n[[Category:Moritz College of Law faculty]]\n[[Category:Law school deans]]\n[[Category:Mercy College (New York) alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1991-93 \u2192 1991\u201393 (3)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gregory_H._Williams"}
